<Prose
  title="Affiliate Disclosure"
  description="How affiliate links work on Styled by Susanne: Amazon Associates and Mavely commissions at no extra cost to you, on pieces Susanne genuinely recommends."
  eyebrow="Policies"
  intro="The plain-English version of how shoppable links on this site pay for themselves."
  dateline="Draft, last updated July 18, 2026"
>
  <h2>The short version</h2>
  <p>
    Some links on this site (mostly on the
    <a href="/looks">Shop the Looks</a> pages) are affiliate links. If you
    click one and buy something, I may earn a small commission. It costs you
    nothing extra, and it helps keep the free styling content coming.
  </p>

  <h2>What an affiliate link actually is</h2>
  <p>
    An affiliate link is a regular product link with a tracking code attached.
    When you purchase through it, the retailer pays me a small percentage of
    the sale. The price you pay is exactly the same as if you had found the
    product on your own; the commission comes out of the retailer&rsquo;s
    side, never yours.
  </p>

  <h2>The programs I participate in</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Amazon Associates.</strong> As an Amazon Associate, I earn from
      qualifying purchases made through my Amazon links.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Mavely.</strong> A creator-commerce platform (similar to LTK)
      that connects my links to a range of retailers. When you buy through a
      Mavely link, the retailer may pay me a commission through that platform.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If I join additional programs, I&rsquo;ll add them here.
  </p>

  <h2>What I will (and won&rsquo;t) link</h2>
  <p>
    I only link pieces I would genuinely recommend to a client or a friend:
    things I own, have styled, or would confidently put in your closet. No
    brand tells me what to feature, and a commission never changes my advice.
    If something isn&rsquo;t worth your money, it doesn&rsquo;t get a link;
    that&rsquo;s the whole deal.
  </p>

  <h2>Where you&rsquo;ll see disclosures</h2>
  <p>
    On every page of this site that includes shoppable links, a plain-language
    disclosure appears before or immediately next to the links themselves,
    not buried in a footer you&rsquo;d have to go hunting for. That placement
    follows the Federal Trade Commission&rsquo;s endorsement guidance, which
    requires that a financial relationship be disclosed clearly and close to
    the recommendation it applies to. The same goes for my social posts: if a
    post contains commissionable links, the post says so.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <p>
    If anything here is unclear, or you spot a link that seems off, I want to
    know. Tell me through the <a href="/book">inquiry form</a> or DM
    @styled.by.susanne on Instagram.
  </p>

  <p>
    Like the other policies on this site, this disclosure is a working draft,
    pending formal legal review before launch. The commitments above stand
    either way.
  </p>
</Prose>
